               <p>843. <persName id="def1-843-18470301" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-843-18470301" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-843-18470301" type="age" value="24"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-843-18470301" type="surname" value="HALEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-843-18470301" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ELIZABETH HALEY</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-843-18470301" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-843-18470301" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-843-18470301" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-843-18470301" type="surname" value="PEEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-843-18470301" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN PEEL</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18470301-843-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470301-843-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470301-843-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp> a like offence.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CLARKE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">LAW</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1125" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1125" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1125" type="surname" value="ROOK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1125" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN ROOK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of George Rook, who keeps a chandler's shop in Creek-place, Bermondsey. On the evening of the 19th Feb., between eight and nine o'clock, Haley came for a half-quartern loaf, and gave me a shilling in payment—I noticed it was a lion shilling—I put it into the till, where there were two other shillings—Haley went away—when she was gone West, the policeman came in—I looked in the till, I found the shilling with</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184703010179"></xptr>
               <p>the lion on, and it was bad—the other two shillings were good, and they had not lions—I bit the lion shilling and gave it to the officer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Haley.</hi> I was not in the shop. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> She is the woman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1126" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1126" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1126" type="surname" value="TORY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1126" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH TORY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a window—I keep a chandler's shop in Albert-place Bermondsey. On Friday evening, the 19th of Feb., Haley came for half an ounce of tea, which came to 1 3/4 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she gave me a sixpence—I gave her 4 1/4 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. change—I put the sixpence in the till—the policeman came in instantly, and asked me what she had given me—I took it out and gave it him—he told me to mark it, an I did—there was no other sixpence in the till.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1127" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1127" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1127" type="surname" value="HASLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1127" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE HASLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of George Hasler—he keeps the Ship public-house at Horslydown. On Friday evening, the 19th of Feb., at a quarter before nine o'clock, Haley came in for a pint of porter, and brought her own jug—I served her, and she gave me a shilling—the policeman was there—he came and told me the woman was offering me bad money—I had not laid the shilling out of my hand—I gave it to him and he took her—I asked where she got it and she told me at the Kent-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1128" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1128" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1128" type="surname" value="WHITLAMB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1128" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WHITLAMB</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 89) On the 19th of Feb. I was in company with West, in plain clothes—I saw the prisoners in company toge<lb></lb>ther in Long-lane, Bermondsey, proceeding in a direction to Mr. Rook's shop—I saw them pass the shop, and at a few yards distance they stood talking for about a minute—Haley went into the shop, and Peel looked in the shop while Haley was in—when Haley came out she went down a turning and stood in the dark till Peel joined her—they then proceeded till they came to Mr. Tory's shop—Haley went in, leaving Peel outside—I saw him pass and repass the shop, and he stood in a dark turning—Haley came out of the shop, they joined again, and went to the Ship—Haley left Peel and went to the bar—she called for a pint of beer, and I saw her lay this shilling down—I cautioned Mr. Hasler, and said she was taking bad money—Haley said she was in the habit of coming in there every night, and if it was bad she did not know it; that she had taken it for some work she had done in the Kent-road—while I was talking to her Peel came in, and was secured.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1129" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1129" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1129" type="surname" value="WEST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1129" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS WEST</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 249.) On the 19th of Feb. I was in company with Whitlamb—I saw the two prisoners in company in Long-lane—they went on to Mr. Rook's shop—Haley went in, and when she came out I went in and received a shilling—I came out and found the prisoners again in company—they went to Mr. Tory's—Haley left Peel a little dis<lb></lb>tance from the shop—she went into the shop, and as soon as she came out I went in and received this sixpence—I came out and saw Peel with the loaf of bread which Haley had brought out of Rook's shop—they then went to the Ship at Shad Thames—Haley went in, leaving Peel outside—he then went in—I followed and took him—I found on him two sixpences, 7 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in coppers, some sugar, and a little tea—I told him I wanted him for uttering base coin with the woman—he said he never saw her before—on the way to the station Haley said, "What is this young man taken for?"—I said for being con<lb></lb>nected with her, in passing counterfeit coin—she said she never saw him before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470301-name-1130" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1130" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1130" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-name-1130" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>MR. JOHN FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. These two shillings are both counterfeit, and from the same mould—the sixpence is also counterfeit.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Haley's Defence.</hi> This man is a perfect stranger to me; what they say against us is quite false; he never was in company with me at all; I was not aware the shilling I had was a bad one; the lady had not time to tell me whether it was bad or good.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">HALEY</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18470301-843-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-843-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-843-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 24.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">PEEL</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18470301-843-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18470301-843-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470301-843-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 19.</p>
